USP Compacts are smaller and lighter than large frame USPs. The reduction in trigger reach and grip circumference increases concealability and enhances shooting ergonomics. Unlike some subcompact semiautomatic pistols that use a difficult to shoot "two-finger grip" frame, the USP Compact uses a narrow, full-hand grip frame with a choice of interchangeable extended or flush-fitting magazine floorplates. This makes the pistol easy to shoot without sacrificing concealability.

Like their large frame predecessors, USP Compacts are designed with the demanding needs of the law enforcement and military shooters in mind. Using a modified linkless Browning-type action, the USP Compact is built to take the punishment of high-energy +P loads.

To reduce the length of the slide and barrel on the USP Compact, the mechanical recoil reduction system found on large frame USPs has been replaced by a specially designed flat compression spring contained in the captive recoil spring assembly by a polymer absorber bushing. Service life is still engineered to exceed 20,000 rounds.

Easy to shoot, simple to maintain; the USP Compact is a reliable, safe, accurate, and highly concealable pistol.

Asking $270 shipped


Daniel Defense Lite Rail III 12.0” (Rifle length) free float hand guard. I bought this rail used, so I don’t have the box. However, the rail is in good condition. It has minor mounting marks visible in the pictures, but other than that it is in great shape. No bends. Comes with FDE and black rubber rail covers. There is enough FDE to cover the whole rail, but I am not sure if there is enough black. The barrel nut started to wear through on the threading, so I contacted Daniel Defense and they sent me a brand new one.


This rail has treated me well, we’ve just grown apart and I just think its time that we went our separate ways. I’m open to different types of payment, but I suppose I prefer Paypal. As long as it doesn’t feel super sketch, it should be okay.


Need more pictures? You got it. But keep in mind I go to school and have two jobs. I try to reply as timely as I can.
Have a question that wasn’t answered here? Ask me, no problem.
My price isn’t in your wheelhouse? Let me know, I try to be fair.


Pictures(15): http://imgur.com/a/hToCl


Daniel Defense Lite Rail III

- 12” Rifle length

- Free floating

- Black

- FDE and black rail covers (not enough black to cover the whole rail).

- Brand new barrel nut

- Barrel nut bracket to mount the rail

- 4 bolts to do the mounting

- Brand new Daniel Defense wrench

- Hex wrench for the 4 bolts

- Free shipping



A few things to be aware of:

- I’m not particularly interested in trades, however, I never say never. 

- Asking $270 shipped. 

- The ID is pretty small, not a lot of clamp on gas blocks fit under this rail, that being said Daniel Defense makes a clamp on gas block that fits wonderfully under it. 

- I have personally tested SLR rifleworks adjustable clamp on gas block, and it does not fit. The set screw version fits uncomfortably close. 

- In case it isn’t obvious, you’ll need to remove your current stock/barrel nut to install this rail. 

- There are minor mounting marks that are visible in the pictures.

- There isn’t enough black rail covers to cover the whole rail, only FDE.

title: For Sale/Trade:  HR Handi-Rifle in 45/70
postcontent:
***Please read entire ad carefully before replying***

I have a synthetic stocked handi rifle in 45/70 caliber. I bought this years ago when I thought I was going to be doing some hog hunting. It never happened, so it lived a short life as a truck gun, then was retired to the gun safe. 
When I last had it out (3 years ago) I went through 22 rounds.  20 of them fired, 2 had light primer strikes.   The 20 that went off were 405 grain lead, the two that didn't were shorter 300 grain rounds. I haven't had the gun out to try since. 
Now, this could indicate that the hammer spring is weak, it could mean that the firing pin didn't go down far enough to hit the shorter rounds solidly, it could mean that the gun is ammo picky, or it might just need disassembly and cleaning in the firing pin channel. I don't know which it is, but as I had that problem last time I have to sell this as-is, and cannot 100% guarantee function with all ammo. 
It's in good, but not great shape. It's like shooting a shoulder mounted howitzer with 500 grain loads, and ammo is spendy if you don't hand load. 
It comes with 38 rounds of ammo, which if you bought it from bi-mart or similar would run you roughly $70.  
Trying to price this fairly due to the 2 failures to fire 3 years ago.
